Accounting for Mismatch Error in Small Area Estimation with Linked Data

Enrico Fabrizi1 Â Â Â Â Â Â  Nicola Salvati2 Â Â Â Â Â Â  Martin Slawski3
1DISES & DSS, UniversitÃ  Cattolica del S. Cuore, Italy
2Department of Economics and Management, University of Pisa, Italy
3Department of Statistics, George Mason University, USA Partially supported by NSF grant #2120318
Abstract

In small area estimation different data sources are integrated in order to produce reliable estimates of target parameters (e.g.,Â a mean or a proportion) for a collection of small subsets (areas) of a finite population. Regression models such as the linear mixed effects model or M-quantile regression are often used to improve the precision of survey sample estimates by leveraging auxiliary information for which means or totals are known at the area level. In many applications, the unit-level linkage of records from different sources is probabilistic and potentially error-prone. In this paper, we present adjustments of the small area predictors that are based on either the linear mixed effects model or M-quantile regression to account for the presence of linkage error. These adjustments are developed from a two-component mixture model that hinges on the assumption of independence of the target and auxiliary variable given incorrect linkage. Estimation and inference is based on composite likelihoods and machinery revolving around the Expectation-Maximization Algorithm. For each of the two regression methods, we propose modified small area predictors and approximations for their mean squared errors. The empirical performance of the proposed approaches is studied in both design-based and model-based simulations that include comparisons to a variety of baselines.


Keywords: Composite Likelihood, Data Integration, Expectation-Maximization Algorithm, Linear Mixed Model, M-quantile Estimation, Mean-Squared Error Estimation, Record Linkage.

1 Introduction

Estimates of finite population parameters such as means or totals that can be obtained from sample surveys may be needed for the population as a whole or for a collection of subsets known as domains or areas, although they are not necessarily geographical regions. A small area estimation problem arises when the area-specific sample sizes are such that estimates relying only on observations from that area have inadequate precision in most or all cases. For instance, this can happen when the estimates are needed for small administrative subdivisions of a country.

Small area estimation methodology is about the integration of a survey and other sources to improve the estimation of area-specific parameters. Recent reviews of the small area literature can be found, e.g., in Rao and Molina, (2015); Pfeffermann, (2013); Sugasawa and Kubokawa, (2020). According to the terminology used in this rich literature, in the present paper we focus on unit-level methods relying on linear models (Rao and Molina,, 2015, chapter 7). In this context a classical scenario is that in addition to the variable of interest a number of auxiliary variables are recorded in the same survey, and means or totals for these auxiliary variables are accurately known from some external source. A model relating the target and the auxiliary variables can therefore be used for improving small area estimates.

In recent years, it has become more common that unit-level values of the auxiliary variables, not only their totals, are from a different data source that is linked at the individual level with the survey sample. Data integration has gained in popularity as information technology makes linkage of the records pertaining to the same individual stored in many registers possible (see for instance Shlomo,, 2014; Sayers etÂ al.,, 2016, for general reviews). On the one hand, this provides significant potential for enhancing small area estimation methods. On the other hand, the linkage of different sources at the micro-level is rarely error-free. Measurement error can be an issue (Boudreaux etÂ al.,, 2015); moreover, missing or false matches can occur whenever unique identifiers are missing or corrupted for a fraction of the cases. Record linkage involve delicate data disclosure issues so that the agent carrying out the linkage and the data analyst operating on the linked data are usually separate individuals. In this paper we will adopt the secondary analyst point of view, assuming that the researcher who does the small area estimation has limited or no information on the linkage process. We will not discuss other potential sources of measurement error and instead focus on the impact of mismatches.

The literature on the secondary analysis of linked data is focused primarily on linear regression, where mismatches are known to cause bias and standard error inflation in regression slope estimates (Scheuren and Winkler,, 1993). A first stream of contributions (Scheuren and Winkler,, 1997; Lahiri and Larsen,, 2005; Chambers,, 2009; DiÂ Consiglio and Tuoto,, 2018; Han and Lahiri,, 2019; Chambers and daÂ Silva,, 2020; Zhang and Tuoto,, 2021) introduce assumptions on the linkage process and focus on bias correction. A second stream of literature noting that the impact of mismatched records is similar to that of (not representative) outliers introduce the use of robust regression with very weak assumptions on the linkage process (Slawski and Ben-David,, 2019; Slawski etÂ al.,, 2021; Chambers etÂ al.,, 2023; Wang etÂ al.,, 2022). The study of linear mixed models with linked data is much more limited (Samart and Chambers,, 2014; Han,, 2018) and so it is for small area estimation (Briscolini etÂ al.,, 2018; Salvati etÂ al.,, 2021).

We focus on small area methods under the assumption that auxiliary and target variables are from different sources, the linkage between the two sources is probabilistic and linkage errors are possible. Similarly to Salvati etÂ al., (2021) we focus on small area predictors based on linear mixed models (LMM) and M-quantile (MQ) regression. Different from Salvati etÂ al., (2021) our assumptions on the information available on the linkage process are weaker, following Slawski etÂ al., (2021, 2023). Specifically, we only assume that the fraction of wrongly linked units in the sample is bounded but no additional information on the linkage errors associated with either individual units or blocks of units is required. At the same time, such information as well as other variables indicative of the match status of the linked records can be readily incorporated.

We represent regression models in the presence of linkage errors as a mixture of two components assuming the independence of target and auxiliary variable given a wrong link has taken place. This approach, which has been proposed by Slawski etÂ al., (2021) for linear regression, is thereby extended to linear mixed models and M-quantile regression. Regarding estimation, we consider an approach based on composite likelihood estimation (Lindsay,, 1988; Varin etÂ al.,, 2011) whose implementation relies on the Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm (Dempster etÂ al.,, 1977).

In summary, we contribute to the literature by proposing a set of new small area predictors constructed from linked data contaminated by mismatch error under weak assumptions regarding the available information on the linkage process. We study the properties of the proposed predictors and develop estimators for their mean squared errors. Our empirical evaluation demonstrates the effectiveness of our approach, achieving a performance that is at least on par with the methods in Salvati etÂ al., (2021) while requiring less information.

The paper is organized as follows. In Section 2, we introduce notation, the assumptions on the linkage process and review linear mixed models and linear M-quantile regression methods on which our small area predictors are based. The predictor of area-level means based on linear mixed models is introduced in Section 3 along with the EM algorithm used for estimation and the proposed mean square error estimator. The same is done for the predictor based on M-quantile regression in Section 4. Section 5 contains an empirical evaluation of the proposed predictors. Specifically, we consider two alternative simulation studies. The first is model-based in the sense that a synthetic population is generated under a linear mixed model with different assumptions on the distribution of random effects and random linkage errors. The second is design-based in that a real finite population is considered in which only sampling and linkage are simulated. The simulation studies are also used to evaluate the empirical properties of the proposed mean square error estimators. Finally, Section 6 contains a discussion of the main results and conclusions. A variety of technical details have been deferred to an appendix.

Note that as far as notation is concerned, the two displays above have made use of the following conventions regarding probability density functions (PDFs), which will be adopted throughout this paper: instead of writing fğ±â€‹(ğ±0)subscriptğ‘“ğ±subscriptğ±0f_{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x}_{0}) for the density of a random vector ğ±ğ±\mathbf{x} evaluated at a point ğ±0subscriptğ±0\mathbf{x}_{0}, we drop the symbol in the subscript and simply write fâ€‹(ğ±0)ğ‘“subscriptğ±0f(\mathbf{x}_{0}) with the convention that the corresponding random variable is inferred from the symbol in the argument. Similar conventions are adopted for joint and conditional PDFs, i.e, we use fâ€‹(ğš0,â€¦,ğ³0)ğ‘“subscriptğš0â€¦subscriptğ³0f(\mathbf{a}_{0},\ldots,\mathbf{z}_{0}) instead of fğšâ€‹â€¦â€‹ğ³â€‹(ğš0,â€¦,ğ³0)subscriptğ‘“ğšâ€¦ğ³subscriptğš0â€¦subscriptğ³0f_{\mathbf{a}\ldots\mathbf{z}}(\mathbf{a}_{0},\ldots,\mathbf{z}_{0}) and fâ€‹(ğ±0|ğ²0)ğ‘“conditionalsubscriptğ±0subscriptğ²0f(\mathbf{x}_{0}|\mathbf{y}_{0}) instead of fğ±|ğ²=ğ²0â€‹(ğ±0)subscriptğ‘“conditionalğ±ğ²subscriptğ²0subscriptğ±0f_{\mathbf{x}|\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{y}_{0}}(\mathbf{x}_{0}), etc. Subscripts in fğ‘“f will be present in case there is no argument. By default, symbols will be boldfaced to indicate vectors or matrices. The dependence of PDFs on parameters is expressed via fâ€‹(â‹…;â€¦)ğ‘“â‹…â€¦f(\cdot\,;\ldots), where â€¦â€¦\ldots represents a list of parameters. For the convenience of the reader, notation that is used frequently in this paper is summarized in Table 1.

2.2 The linear mixed effects SA model

The nested error regression model is very popular in small area estimation since the original proposal of Battese etÂ al., (1988). In our notation, let us assume that the following model holds at the population level:

where subscripts Î»jsubscriptğœ†ğ‘—\lambda_{j} indicate the associated sub-vectors and row submatrices, respectively. For now, gğ‘”g is assumed to be fixed even though gğ‘”g is generally unknown; This aspect revisited in Â§Â§\S3.1 below222Since gğ‘”g is assumed to be independent of linkage error (cf.Â Eq.Â (1)), its estimation does not require any specific adjustment.. We note that (6) is more adequately referred to as a composite likelihood (Lindsay,, 1988; Varin etÂ al.,, 2011) as opposed to a (proper) likelihood. This is because (6) may involve products over terms that are not independent. Specifically, the likelihood contributions involving the mismatch indicators are generally dependent since they are derived from a random permutation. As a simple example, consider a random permutation Ï€ğœ‹\pi on {1,2}12\{1,2\} that swaps the order of the two indices with probability Î±âˆˆ(0,1)ğ›¼01\alpha\in(0,1). In this case, (1âˆ’Î±)=ğâ¡(Ï€â€‹(1)=1,Ï€â€‹(2)=2)â‰ ğâ¡(Ï€â€‹(1)=1)â‹…ğâ¡(Ï€â€‹(2)=2)=(1âˆ’Î±)21ğ›¼ğğœ‹11ğœ‹22â‹…ğğœ‹11ğğœ‹22superscript1ğ›¼2(1-\alpha)=\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\pi(1)=1,\,\pi(2)=2)\neq\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\pi(1)=1)\cdot\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\pi(2)=2)=(1-\alpha)^{2}. This example relates to record linkage when one-to-one matchings are enforced: given two records ağ‘a and bğ‘b in the first file with correct matches aâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²a^{\prime} and bâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²b^{\prime} in the second file, respectively, then incorrectly matching ağ‘a to bâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²b^{\prime} will cause bğ‘b to be mismatched as well since the requirement of a one-to-match entails that (i) at least one match has to found for bğ‘b and (ii) bğ‘b cannot match to bâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²b^{\prime} since none of the records can appear in more than one linked pair.

Regardless, existing frameworks for composite likelihood inference justify the use of (6): in a nutshell, under suitable regularity conditions estimators defined as maximizers of products of valid marginal likelihood contributions constructed from data subsets of any size (individual observations, pairs of observations, etc.) with possible dependencies across those subsets enjoy asymptotic properties similar to conventional maximum likelihood estimators; their asymptotic covariance matrix exhibits the usual â€œsandwich formâ€ that arises in the more general setting of Mğ‘€M- and Zğ‘Z-estimators (e.g., Stefanski and Boos,, 2002).

The benefit of the composite likelihood (6) is that it yields a concise expression that retains most of the structure of the conventional linear mixed model likelihood and enables computationally tractable inference as detailed in Â§Â§\S3.1 and Appendix B.

2.3 The linear M-quantile model

Similarly to the more popular quantile regression (Koenker and Bassett,, 1978), M-quantile (MQ) regression (Breckling and Chambers,, 1988) is a semi-parametric method where M-estimation ideas are introduced in quantile regression to make it more flexible in terms of the balance to strike between robustness and efficiency. Yu and Moyeed, (2001) use the asymmetric Laplace distribution to obtain a parametric representation of quantile regression. Along the same line, for the purposes of this paper we present the MQ regression model using a working likelihood introduced by Bianchi etÂ al., (2018). Let us assume that at the population level the following model holds:

3 The LMM-based predictor

In the next two sections, we study the approaches outlined in Â§Â§\S2.2 and Â§Â§\S2.3 and the resulting predictors for the area means in more detail. We start with the former approach. Before discussing the predictor and estimation of its MSE, we first sketch our computational algorithm for estimating the underlying parameters, with detailed computations relegated to Appendix B.

3.1 Computational algorithm

Estimation of the parameters ğœ½âˆ—=(ğœ·âˆ—,Ïƒâˆ—2,ğšºâˆ—,ğœ¶âˆ—)subscriptğœ½subscriptğœ·superscriptsubscriptğœ2subscriptğšºsubscriptğœ¶\bm{\theta}_{*}=(\bm{\beta}_{*},\sigma_{*}^{2},\bm{\Sigma}_{*},\bm{\alpha}_{*}) is based on the integrated complete data (composite)-likelihood arising from (6) via integration over the latent variables {(Î»j,ğœ¸j)}j=1Dsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğœ†ğ‘—subscriptğœ¸ğ‘—ğ‘—1ğ·\{(\lambda_{j},\bm{\gamma}_{j})\}_{j=1}^{D}, i.e.,

dâ€‹ğœ¸1â€‹â€¦â€‹dâ€‹ğœ¸D.ğ‘‘subscriptğœ¸1â€¦ğ‘‘subscriptğœ¸ğ·\displaystyle\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\;\;d{\bm{\gamma}}_{1}\ldots d\bm{\gamma}_{D}. (11)

where the summations are over all possible realizations {â„“j}subscriptâ„“ğ‘—\{\ell_{j}\} of the configurations of mismatches in area jğ‘—j, which is given by ğ’«jsubscriptğ’«ğ‘—\mathcal{P}_{j} â€“ the power set of {1,â€¦,nj}1â€¦subscriptğ‘›ğ‘—\{1,\ldots,n_{j}\}, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤D1ğ‘—ğ·1\leq j\leq D. The representation (11) indicates that direct maximization of Lğ¿L poses a significant computational challenge; in fact, the mere evaluation of the integrated likelihood alone is intricate. For this reason, we resort to the EM algorithm (Dempster etÂ al.,, 1977). The E-step requires considerable computational effort given that the latent {Î»j}subscriptğœ†ğ‘—\{\lambda_{j}\} take values in the power sets {ğ’«j}j=1Dsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ’«ğ‘—ğ‘—1ğ·\{\mathcal{P}_{j}\}_{j=1}^{D}. In order to ensure scalability of the E-step to larger sample sizes {nj}subscriptğ‘›ğ‘—\{n_{j}\}, we develop a Monte Carlo approximation based on separable updates of the individual mismatch indicators {miâ€‹j(s)}superscriptsubscriptğ‘šğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘ \{m_{ij}^{(s)}\} via Gibbs sampling (e.g. Robert and Casella,, 2013). Note that one-by-one updating of the {miâ€‹j(s)}superscriptsubscriptğ‘šğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘ \{m_{ij}^{(s)}\} in the exact E-step is not possible given the dependence of the {yiâ€‹j}i=1njsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘–1subscriptğ‘›ğ‘—\{y_{ij}\}_{i=1}^{n_{j}} induced by ğœ¸jsubscriptğœ¸ğ‘—\bm{\gamma}_{j}, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤D1ğ‘—ğ·1\leq j\leq D, and the fact that the E-step involves the joint expectation of {(Î»j,ğœ¸j)}subscriptğœ†ğ‘—subscriptğœ¸ğ‘—\{(\lambda_{j},\bm{\gamma}_{j})\} given the data and current values of the parameters.

By comparison, the resulting M-step is straightforward. The update for ğœ·ğœ·\bm{\beta} turns out to reduce to a weighted least squares problem. The updates for the variance components ğšºğšº\bm{\Sigma} and Ïƒ2superscriptğœ2\sigma^{2} have simple and computationally tractable closed form solutions. Finally, the update for ğœ¶ğœ¶\bm{\alpha} may require iterative algorithms depending on the complexity of the function hâ„h; in some cases, closed form updates are obtained. Detailed derivations of the E-step (both in the exact case and with the use of the proposed Monte-Carlo approximation) and the M-step can be found in Appendix B. Further implementation details. So far, we have assumed that the density gğ‘”g (cf.Â Eq.Â (3)) is known which is not the case in practice. Note that estimation of gğ‘”g â€“ the marginal PDF of the sampled yğ‘¦yâ€™s â€“ is not affected by mismatch error and thus does not require the use of specific strategies to deal with such error. Straightforward approaches include kernel density estimation (KDE) or the use of (simplified) parametric models, e.g., {yiâ€‹j(s)}âˆ¼Nâ€‹(Î¼g,Ïƒg2)similar-tosuperscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘ ğ‘subscriptğœ‡ğ‘”superscriptsubscriptğœğ‘”2\{y_{ij}^{(s)}\}\sim N(\mu_{g},\sigma_{g}^{2}) if the total number of sampled units is too small for the use of KDE. According to the expression for gğ‘”g given the linear mixed model (4) provided at the end of Appendix A has a finite Gaussian mixture representation. While the locations and scales of this mixture (3) are unknown, they can be substituted given pilot estimators for ğœ·âˆ—subscriptğœ·\bm{\beta}_{*}, ğšºâˆ—subscriptğšº\bm{\Sigma}_{*}, and Ïƒâˆ—2superscriptsubscriptğœ2\sigma_{*}^{2}. Possible pilot estimators include the naive estimator (ignoring mismatch error) given the linear mixed model (4) or one of the proposals developed in Salvati etÂ al., (2021) if estimates for block-wise mismatch rates are available. The resulting estimate of gğ‘”g, say g^(0)superscript^ğ‘”0\widehat{g}^{(0)}, can be used in a first round of EM iterations as detailed, yielding estimators (ğœ·^,ğšº^,Ïƒ^2)^ğœ·^ğšºsuperscript^ğœ2(\widehat{\bm{\beta}},\widehat{\bm{\Sigma}},\widehat{\sigma}^{2}) than can in turn be used to update the locations and scales in the mixture (3), yielding a refined estimate g^(1)superscript^ğ‘”1\widehat{g}^{(1)} to be used in another round of EM iterations to obtain refined estimates of the parameters. This process can be continued iteratively.

Empirical results on the performance of the proposed approach reported in this paper do not make use of the described iterative scheme since vanilla KDE with a Gaussian kernel and default choices of the bandwidth achieved satisfactory performance. Similarly, initialization of the EM iterations with the naive (REML or ML) estimates in line with (4) worked well even though improved initialization could be attempted.

In order to find the large-sample distribution of (ğœ·~,ğœ¶~)~ğœ·~ğœ¶(\widetilde{\bm{\beta}},\widetilde{\bm{\alpha}}), we leverage properties of composite maximum likelihood estimators (cf. Varin etÂ al.,, 2011) in a super-population setting. Specifically, it holds that

MSE estimation in the general case. Since the variance components are typically unknown, we replace them with the corresponding estimates produced by our approach. We then apply the scheme outlined in the previous paragraph, ignoring the uncertainty associated with the variance components. We show empirically that the resulting MSE estimates are still accurate. Given the inherently non-linear nature of the proposed predictor, MSE estimation is associated with significant technical challenges, and accounting for uncertainty from estimation of the variance components is considered out of the scope of the present paper and left for future work.

4 The MQ-based predictor

4.1 The predictor

In the application of MQ regression to small area estimation, the construction of the predictor hinges on the unit-level MQ coefficients and their area-level averages that are used to capture the unobserved heterogeneity at the area level. As noted in Chambers and Tzavidis, (2006), at the population level we can define observation-specific quantiles Ï„iâ€‹jâˆˆ(0,1)subscriptğœğ‘–ğ‘—01\tau_{ij}\in(0,1) so that yiâ€‹j=ğ±iâ€‹jâŠ¤â€‹ğœ·Ï„iâ€‹jsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘—superscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–ğ‘—topsubscriptğœ·subscriptğœğ‘–ğ‘—y_{ij}=\mathbf{x}_{ij}^{\top}\bm{\beta}_{\tau_{ij}}. As MQ regression is based on a smooth loss function for each yiâ€‹jsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘—y_{ij} we have exactly one such Ï„iâ€‹jsubscriptğœğ‘–ğ‘—\tau_{ij}. The area-level population mean can be represented as

5 Empirical evaluation

In this section, we present the results of simulations to showcase the empirical performance of the two approaches proposed above. We consider both a model-based and a design-based simulation. In the former, data are generated that precisely follow the linear mixed effects SA model (4) with mismatch error introduced uniformly at random according to a procedure described below in a way that guarantees that the assumptions in Â§Â§\S2.1 are satisfied. We also consider a modification that includes heteroscedastic random effects and the presence of outliers. In the design-based simulation, only the sampling of units and the record linkage process are generated synthetically. The specifics of the two simulations are adopted from Salvati etÂ al., (2021). In the sequel, we review these specifics and how the approaches proposed herein are run in each case. Moreover, we present comparisons to several baseline competitors.

5.1 Model-based simulation

In the model-based simulations, the synthetic finite population consists of D=40ğ·40D=40 areas with population sizes Nj=100subscriptğ‘ğ‘—100N_{j}=100, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤D1ğ‘—ğ·1\leq j\leq D. Data are generated according to the linear mixed effect models (4) with a single predictor variable and area-specific intercepts. Specifically,

When reporting the results, references to specific methods are made as follows. Under scenario (i) the linear mixed model-based predictors and the MQ-based predictor are referred to as Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab, respectively; in scenario (ii) the two predictors are referred to as Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘EBLUPME~{}b and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘MQME~{}b; finally, under the last scenario where neither mismatch rates nor blocks are known, the estimators are referred to as Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸EBLUPME and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸MQME. The following baselines are run for the sake of comparison: the standard EBLUP (Rao and Molina,, 2015), the EBLUP adjustment for linkage error in Salvati etÂ al., (2021) (denoted by Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ‹†ğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆsuperscriptğ‘ƒâ‹†EBLUP^{\star}), the estimator based on the MQ regression model (Chambers and Tzavidis,, 2006) and the adjustment of this method for linkage error developed in Salvati etÂ al., (2021). Moreover, the results for the EBLUP and MQ-based predictor in the absence of mismatches (referred to as â€œoraclesâ€) are reported to evaluate the loss of the proposed predictors in terms of bias and efficiency in case of mismatches.

Table 2 shows the percentage relative bias of the form 100â‹…(Î¸^Â¯âˆ’Î¸âˆ—)/Î¸âˆ—â‹…100Â¯^ğœƒsubscriptğœƒsubscriptğœƒ100\cdot(\overline{\widehat{\theta}}-\theta_{*})/\theta_{*} with regard to the estimation of the underlying parameters. In estimating regression coefficients, neither models with adjustment for the presence of mismatches exhibit any prevailing sign for the bias under all simulation scenarios. As expected the linear mixed effects and the M-quantile models without adjustment produce biased estimates of the regression coefficients. The two methods differ substantially in estimating Î±ğ›¼\alpha. The M-quantile models exhibit downward bias (around 12%percent1212\% to 13%percent1313\% in scenario (0,0) and 6%percent66\% to 7%percent77\% in scenario (0.1,0.03)), whereas the estimates obtained with the proposed linear mixed models exhibit lower bias (around âˆ’1%percent1-1\% in scenario (0,0) and 6%percent66\% in setting (0.1,0.03)). A likely explanation is that M-quantile regression better accommodates outliers and therefore tends to identify a smaller fraction of wrong links as such. Moreover, the relative bias results that are set out in Table 2 show a high level of bias for the estimators of the parameter Ïƒâˆ—2superscriptsubscriptğœ2\sigma_{*}^{2} for the linear mixed effects models without adjustment for the presence of mismatches as well as with the correction suggested by Salvati etÂ al., (2021). This increase in bias is most pronounced when there are outliers at individual and area levels. As expected, under the latter also the estimation of Î£âˆ—subscriptÎ£\Sigma_{*} is affected, with all of the investigated methods exhibiting upward bias. This result suggests a robustification of the estimating equations of the linear mixed effects models as proposed in Salvati etÂ al., (2021) as a possible direction for future research.

Next, we examine the performance of the various small area predictors. For each estimator and for each small area, we computed the Monte Carlo estimate of the empirical bias and the empirical MSE. For a given area, the bias of an estimator is defined as the value of the average difference between the estimate and the corresponding true simulated small area mean, average being taken over simulations. The MSE is defined as the average squared difference between the estimate and the corresponding true simulated small area mean, average being taken over simulations.

Figures 2 and 3 present the distribution of the area-specific values of the empirical bias and MSE of the small area estimators under the two settings. In scenario (0,0) we see that the proposed estimators Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab, Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab, Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘EBLUPME~{}b, Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘MQME~{}b, Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸EBLUPME and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸MQME that allow for linkage error work well in terms of both bias and MSE compared with the Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ‹†ğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆsuperscriptğ‘ƒâ‹†EBLUP^{\star}, Mâ€‹Qâ‹†ğ‘€superscriptğ‘„â‹†MQ^{\star} and unmodified EBLUP and M-quantile-based predictors that ignore linkage error. The former are less biased and variable than the latter. Under scenario (0.1,0.03) the Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘EBLUPME~{}b and the Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab estimators perform best in terms of bias, whereas Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab, Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab perform best in terms of MSE. These results are expected because Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab have the advantage of being equipped with the mismatch rates for each block.

It is worth emphasizing that the predictors Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸EBLUPME and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸MQME, which correct for linkage error when neither mismatch rates nor blocks are known, achieve a performance both in terms of bias and MSE that is roughly on par with estimators correcting for linkage errors using a richer set of information. In particular, we note that Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab exhibits a lower MSE than Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ‹†ğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆsuperscriptğ‘ƒâ‹†EBLUP^{\star} and to a lesser extent the same is true for Mâ€‹Qâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘ğ‘MQ~{}ab with respect to Mâ€‹Qâ‹†ğ‘€superscriptğ‘„â‹†MQ^{\star}. When the same set of information is available, the mixture specification proposed in this paper seems to be more effective in dealing with both representative and mismatch-induced outliers than their counterparts proposed previously in Salvati etÂ al., (2021). In this context, according to a connection drawn in Slawski etÂ al., (2021), we note the relationship between the two-component mixture model adopted for the approaches in this paper and the minimization of a â€œcappedâ€ loss function resembling Tukeyâ€™s celebrated biweight loss function. The latter is well known for its effectiveness in reducing the influence of large errors (e.g., Maronna etÂ al.,, 2006, p.Â 30).

With regard to MSE estimation, the boxplots in Figure 4 are used to explore the variability in the RMSE ratio defined as the ratio of the average estimated RMSE for each area to the true RMSE. The left panels refer to the case (0,0), whereas the right panels present the ratios for the case (0.1,0.03). It can be seen that the MSE estimators of the two proposed approaches perform well especially for the MQ-based predictors.

The performance of the various small area predictors accounting for linkage error investigated in this study suggest that they are robust in the presence of such error as well as when additionally outliers are present.

5.2 Design-based simulation

In this section, we adopt the simulation setup in Salvati etÂ al., (2021) to evaluate the performance of the estimators proposed in the case of a finite, fixed population and a realistic sampling method. The population we consider is synthetic but based on real data. It is derived from the European Statistical System Data Integration project (ESSnet, cf. McLeod etÂ al.,, 2011) and the Survey on Household Income and Wealth, Bank of Italy (SHIW), which provides openly available anonymized data. Specifically, the synthetic ESSnet population includes information on over 26,000 individuals, encompassing variables such as first and last name, sex, and date of birth. Additionally, two supplementary variables, annual income, and domain indicators have been incorporated. The domain indicators represent 18 areas formed through the aggregation of Italian administrative regions, with population sizes ranging from 102 to 3262 individuals and an average of 1407. The setup of our simulation study is designed in close similarity to that in Briscolini etÂ al., (2018).

We conduct a realistic record linkage and Small Area Estimation (SAE) simulation experiment by perturbing the original ESSnet dataset. These perturbations involve the introduction of missing values and typographical errors in potential linking variables such as name, surname, gender, and date of birth. Furthermore, for the purpose of this simulation study, annual consumption obtained from the SHIW survey is also considered and will be used as the target variable in estimation.

We employ the classical probabilistic record linkage procedure proposed by Fellegi and Sunter, (1969) and Jaro, (1989). This involves utilizing the compare.linkage function from the RecordLinkage package in R (Sariyar and Borg,, 2020) to link the perturbed dataset with the original register population. The linkage is performed using surname as the key variable, with age categorized into four groups and domain serving as blocking variables. This implies that mismatch error only occurs within but not across domains, in line with the setting in Salvati etÂ al., (2021).

The linking process is done sample-to-register so that every sampled unit is linked to precisely one unit in the register. Although the linking is one-to-one, it is evidently incomplete and thus not perfectly in line with the assumption of complete linkage made in Â§Â§\S2.1. Empirically it turns out that the proposed predictors are not sensitive to this departure. Given that the linkage in this scenario is contingent on the realized sample, the proportion of correct links for the four age categories varies from one sample to another (Salvati etÂ al.,, 2021).

The objective of the design-based simulation is to assess and contrast the effectiveness of various estimators along with their estimated MSEs in the absence of any distributional assumptions regarding the data-generating process, with annual mean consumption per domain serving as the target of interest (yğ‘¦y). This assessment is conducted through repeated sampling from a synthetic fixed population, using annual income as the auxiliary variable (xğ‘¥x). A total of 1,000 independent random samples, each consisting of 268 units, are drawn from the synthetic fixed population mentioned earlier. These samples are generated by randomly selecting units across the 18 domains, with the sample sizes within each domain being proportional to their respective population sizes. However, if the resulting sample size is less than 5, the domain sample size is fixed at 5.

The same estimators as in the model-based simulation are compared. They are run with the same configurations as described in the previous subsection. For each estimator and for each small area, we computed the Monte Carlo estimate of the relative bias (RB) and the relative root MSE (RRMSE). The relative bias of an estimator yÂ¯^jsubscript^Â¯ğ‘¦ğ‘—\widehat{\overline{y}}_{j} of the actual mean yÂ¯jsubscriptÂ¯ğ‘¦ğ‘—{\overline{y}}_{j} is the average across simulations of the errors yÂ¯^jâˆ’yÂ¯jsubscript^Â¯ğ‘¦ğ‘—subscriptÂ¯ğ‘¦ğ‘—\widehat{\overline{y}}_{j}-{\overline{y}}_{j} divided by the corresponding value of yÂ¯jsubscriptÂ¯ğ‘¦ğ‘—{\overline{y}}_{j} and its RRMSE is the square root of the average across simulations of the squares of these errors, again divided by the value of yÂ¯jsubscriptÂ¯ğ‘¦ğ‘—{\overline{y}}_{j}, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤D=181ğ‘—ğ·181\leq j\leq D=18.

Figure 5 shows boxplots of area-specific values of the RB (top panel) and the RRMSE (bottom panel) of the small area predictors in the design-based experiment, both reported as percentages. From these plots we can see that the estimators proposed herein (Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab, Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘EBLUPME~{}b, Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘EBLUPME~{}b, Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab, Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘MQME~{}b and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸MQME) work well in terms of both bias and RRMSE compared with the unmodified EBLUP and MQ-based predictors that ignore linkage error and the Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ‹†ğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆsuperscriptğ‘ƒâ‹†EBLUP^{\star} and Mâ€‹Qâ‹†ğ‘€superscriptğ‘„â‹†MQ^{\star} (Salvati etÂ al.,, 2021). The Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab performs best in terms of bias and efficiency, whereas the Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab is the predictor which performs best in RRMSE within the set of MQ estimators. These results are expected because the Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘EBLUPME~{}ab and the Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eâ€‹aâ€‹bğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘MQME~{}ab exploit information that are not used by the other proposed predictors, namely the true mismatch rates and blocks. From this perspective, the performance of the estimators Eâ€‹Bâ€‹Lâ€‹Uâ€‹Pâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ¸ğµğ¿ğ‘ˆğ‘ƒğ‘€ğ¸EBLUPME and Mâ€‹Qâ€‹Mâ€‹Eğ‘€ğ‘„ğ‘€ğ¸MQME that lack this information is convincing. The reported results also indicate that estimators that correct for linkage error seem to offer the most balanced performance in terms of both bias and MSE for this population.

Regarding MSE estimation, Figure 6 shows the area-specific values of the RMSE ratios of the MSE estimators in the design-based experiment. In particular, the RMSE ratio is defined as the ratio of the average estimated RMSE for each area to the actually incurred RMSE. We observe that the MSE estimators proposed in Â§Â§\S 4.3 behave very similarly for MQ-based predictors accounting for linkage error. The resulting estimates align quite well with the actual area-specific MSEs of these predictors. While still roughly capturing the area-specific MSEs of the three associated predictors, the MSE estimates of the EBLUP-type predictor presented in Â§Â§\S3.3 exhibit a visible downward bias. Note that the EBLUP-type machinery relies much more strongly on distributional assumptions, which are potentially questionable in this specific application.

6 Discussion and Conclusions

Record linkage is a useful tool for taking advantage of the additional value that can be obtained by combining multiple data sources containing complementary pieces of information. Small area estimation is a domain in which record linkage can be utilized to obtain unit-level covariates for creating powerful small area predictors. It is often tacitly assumed that the associated linkage process is free of errors, particularly in the secondary analysis setting studied herein since data analysts may simply rely on the correctness of the linked records provided. In this paper, we have proposed an approach that adjusts two popular regression-based small area predictors for possible mismatch error in the underlying linked data set. The methods we propose can be seen also as a robustification of the two predictors. In fact, false matches can generate non-representative outliers, and we modify the predictors to downweigh them; if outliers are present for other reasons our methods can accommodate them, too.

Missed matches, i.e., correct links not identified as such, is the second type of error that is presumably equally important. Such missing links are generally not ignorable and not accounting for this possibility can thus introduce selection bias. This prompts the need for methods that can account for both types of errors. Concerning avenues of future research in addition to those pointed out in the body of the paper, we note that the proposed approach relies on strong ignorability assumptions associated with the latent mismatch indicators. It is worth investigating to what extent these assumptions can be relaxed. Second, the discussion in this paper is confined to unit-level small area estimation based on linear regression. Future work could extend our approach to i) outcome variables (e.g., proportions or counts) mandating the use of non-linear regression models, and ii) area-level models such as the popular Fay-Herriot model (Fay and Herriot,, 1979).

In this case, the update for Î±ğ›¼\alpha is seen to be the average of the {1âˆ’Ï‰iâ€‹j(t)}1superscriptsubscriptğœ”ğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘¡\{1-\omega_{ij}^{(t)}\}. Remark. We note that the EM algorithm is a simply a computational vehicle (a specific majorizationâ€“minimization (MM) algorithm, cf.Â Hunter and Lange, (2004)) for optimizing likelihood functions involving integrals over latent variables. As such, it is immaterial whether the function to be optimized arises from a â€œgenuineâ€ likelihood or from a composite likelihood, and evaluation of ğâ¡(Î»j=â„“j;ğœ½(t))ğsubscriptğœ†ğ‘—subscriptâ„“ğ‘—superscriptğœ½ğ‘¡\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\lambda_{j}=\ell_{j};\bm{\theta}^{(t)}), 1â‰¤jâ‰¤D1ğ‘—ğ·1\leq j\leq D, in the E-step according to (B.4) is justified.

B.2 Monte Carlo Approximation (MC-EM)

In this subsection, we provide details on the approximation of integrals (B.2) in the E-step via Monte Carlo integration in the spirit of Wei and Tanner, (1990), i.e., sampling from the distribution of the latent variables {ğœ¸j,Î»j}j=1Dsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğœ¸ğ‘—subscriptğœ†ğ‘—ğ‘—1ğ·\{\bm{\gamma}_{j},\lambda_{j}\}_{j=1}^{D} given ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} and the current parameters ğœ½(t)superscriptğœ½ğ‘¡\bm{\theta}^{(t)}. As a result, we obtain an approximation to the expected complete data negative (pseudo)-log-likelihood (B.7), side-stepping the combinatorial barrier that is associated with an exact E-step computation as discussed in the previous subsection. Sampling from the joint distribution of ğœ¸j,Î»j|ğ’Ÿ;ğœ½(t)subscriptğœ¸ğ‘—conditionalsubscriptğœ†ğ‘—ğ’Ÿsuperscriptğœ½ğ‘¡\bm{\gamma}_{j},\lambda_{j}|\mathcal{D};\bm{\theta}^{(t)} is facilitated via Gibbs sampling: we alternate between sampling of (i) Î»j|ğœ¸j,ğ’Ÿ;ğœ½(t)conditionalsubscriptğœ†ğ‘—subscriptğœ¸ğ‘—ğ’Ÿsuperscriptğœ½ğ‘¡\lambda_{j}|\bm{\gamma}_{j},\mathcal{D};\bm{\theta}^{(t)} and (ii) ğœ¸j|Î»j,ğ’Ÿ;ğœ½(t)conditionalsubscriptğœ¸ğ‘—subscriptğœ†ğ‘—ğ’Ÿsuperscriptğœ½ğ‘¡\bm{\gamma}_{j}|\lambda_{j},\mathcal{D};\bm{\theta}^{(t)}, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤D1ğ‘—ğ·1\leq j\leq D. In fact, as we elaborate below, both (i) and (ii) reduce to straightforward tasks: the former reduces to independent sampling of mismatch indicators {miâ€‹j}subscriptğ‘šğ‘–ğ‘—\{m_{ij}\}, whereas the latter involves sampling from a normal distribution. In particular, the ability to reduce sampling of {Î»j}subscriptğœ†ğ‘—\{\lambda_{j}\} to independent (Bernoulli) sampling of mismatch indicators breaks the combinatorial barrier that is associated with the exact E-step.
